results.name: Number of factorizations of n into distinct, pairwise indivisible factors greater than 1.
link: Antti Karttunen, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..16384
Antti Karttunen, Data supplement: n, a(n) computed for n = 1..100000
mathematica: facs[n_] := If[n <= 1, {{}}, Join@@Table[Map[Prepend[#, d] &, Select[facs[n/d], Min@@ # >= d &]], {d, Rest[Divisors[n]]}]]; Table[Length[Select[facs[n], UnsameQ@@ # && Select[Tuples[Union[#], 2], UnsameQ@@ # && Divisible@@ # &] == {} &]], {n, 100}]
program: (PARI) A305150(n, m=n, facs=List([])) = if(1==n, 1, my(s=0, newfacs); fordiv(n, d, if((d>1)&&(d<=m)&&factorback(apply(x -> (x%d),Vec(facs))), newfacs = List(facs); listput(newfacs,d); s += A305150(n/d, d-1, newfacs))); (s)); \\ _Antti Karttunen_, Dec 06 2018
